  <p><strong>Quick Answer:</strong> Cabernet Sauvignon is the world's most planted wine grape, producing full-bodied reds with blackcurrant, cedar, and tobacco notes. Best paired with red meat, aged cheeses, and robust dishes. Look for wines from Napa Valley, Bordeaux, and Australia.</p>

  <h2>Cabernet Sauvignon Overview</h2>

  <p>Cabernet Sauvignon is the world's most planted wine grape and the king of red wines. Known for its full body, high tannins, and exceptional aging potential, this noble grape produces some of the most celebrated wines globally.</p>

  <h2>Tasting Profile</h2>

  <h3>Primary Characteristics</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Color:</strong> Deep purple to garnet</li>
    <li><strong>Aroma:</strong> Blackcurrant, cedar, tobacco, vanilla</li>
    <li><strong>Palate:</strong> Full-bodied with firm tannins</li>
    <li><strong>Finish:</strong> Long and structured</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Classic Flavor Profile</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Fruit:</strong> Blackcurrant, blackberry, dark cherry</li>
    <li><strong>Herbs:</strong> Mint, eucalyptus, green bell pepper</li>
    <li><strong>Oak:</strong> Vanilla, cedar, tobacco, chocolate</li>
    <li><strong>Earth:</strong> Graphite, mineral, leather</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Top Cabernet Sauvignon Regions</h2>

  <h3>Napa Valley, California</h3>
  <p>The gold standard for New World Cabernet Sauvignon. Rich, powerful wines with ripe fruit and excellent aging potential.</p>

  <h3>Bordeaux, France</h3>
  <p>Home of the original Cabernet blends. Elegant, structured wines that define Old World sophistication.</p>

  <h3>Coonawarra, Australia</h3>
  <p>Famous terra rossa soil produces distinctive eucalyptus and mint notes with excellent structure.</p>

  <h2>Wine Recommendations by Price</h2>

  <h3>Under $20</h3>
  <p><strong>Columbia Crest Grand Estates ($15):</strong> Washington State value with consistent quality and approachable style.</p>

  <h3>$20-50 Range</h3>
  <p><strong>Stag's Leap Wine Cellars Artemis ($35):</strong> Napa Valley elegance with balanced fruit and oak integration.</p>

  <h3>Premium ($50+)</h3>
  <p><strong>Caymus Napa Valley ($85):</strong> Rich, opulent style that showcases Napa's power and finesse.</p>

  <h2>Food Pairing Guide</h2>

  <h3>Perfect Matches</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Grilled ribeye steak and lamb</li>
    <li>Hard aged cheeses (Aged Cheddar, Pecorino)</li>
    <li>Dark chocolate and espresso</li>
    <li>Herb-crusted roasts</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Avoid Pairing With</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Delicate fish (overpowers)</li>
    <li>Very spicy Asian cuisine</li>
    <li>Light salads and vegetables</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Serving & Storage</h2>

  <p><strong>Serving Temperature:</strong> 60-65°F (16-18°C)</p>
  <p><strong>Decanting:</strong> 1-2 hours for young wines, 30 minutes for mature</p>
  <p><strong>Glassware:</strong> Large Bordeaux glass for optimal aeration</p>
  <p><strong>Aging Potential:</strong> 10-20+ years for quality examples</p>

